which is much smaller in size,

87
00:03:37,560 --> 00:03:38,560
portable, and versatile to use

88
00:03:39,080 --> 00:03:40,080
as you can wrap it around objects

89
00:03:41,360 --> 00:03:42,360
like a pole or tree.

90
00:03:43,080 --> 00:03:44,080
Tip number three is body posture.

91
00:03:45,000 --> 00:03:46,000
Whenever shooting handheld,

92
00:03:46,780 --> 00:03:47,780
you want to keep your
arm close to your body

93
00:03:49,690 --> 00:03:50,690
and create a two-point contact

94
00:03:51,560 --> 00:03:52,560
as this will help smoothen out the shot.

95
00:03:53,910 --> 00:03:54,910
You also want to walk heel to toe

96
00:03:55,470 --> 00:03:56,470
to avoid up and down movements.

97
00:03:57,630 --> 00:03:58,630
This way, you will make your shots

98
00:03:58,780 --> 00:03:59,780
look much more natural.

99
00:04:00,410 --> 00:04:01,410
When holding your phone,

100
00:04:01,470 --> 00:04:02,470
try to hold it in a way

101
00:04:03,280 --> 00:04:04,280
with one hand supporting
the bottom of the phone

102
00:04:05,970 --> 00:04:06,970
and the other hand placed

103
00:04:07,330 --> 00:04:08,330
towards the center of the phone.

104
00:04:09,390 --> 00:04:10,390
You will notice that you'll
have much better grip

105
00:04:11,640 --> 00:04:12,640
and can therefore control your
camera movements much better.

106
00:04:15,130 --> 00:04:16,130
Depending on your shot,

107
00:04:16,420 --> 00:04:17,420
this isn't always possible,

108
00:04:17,850 --> 00:04:18,850
but whenever you can,

109
00:04:19,040 --> 00:04:20,040
try to apply this method.

110
00:04:20,870 --> 00:04:21,870
Also, while recording your videos,

111
00:04:22,440 --> 00:04:23,440
try to hold your breath

112
00:04:24,020 --> 00:04:25,020
as this will also help make
the shakes less apparent.

113
00:04:26,920 --> 00:04:27,920
Tip number four is to make sure
you get a variety of shots.

114
00:04:30,060 --> 00:04:31,060
Try to shoot as many angles,

115
00:04:31,950 --> 00:04:32,950
focal lengths and movements

116
00:04:33,500 --> 00:04:34,500
as you can think of

117
00:04:34,810 --> 00:04:35,810
to make your videos more interesting.

118
00:04:37,090 --> 00:04:38,090
Include wide-angle shots
to establish the scene,

119
00:04:39,870 --> 00:04:40,870
but also capture detailed shots

120
00:04:41,950 --> 00:04:42,950
that are important for the story.

121
00:04:44,150 --> 00:04:45,150
I often see people doing the mistake

122
00:04:45,870 --> 00:04:46,870
of just capturing wide shots,

123
00:04:47,640 --> 00:04:48,640
which can quickly get boring.

124
00:04:49,390 --> 00:04:50,390
Shoot the scene from different angles

125
00:04:51,000 --> 00:04:52,000
so that you can cut between the shots

126
00:04:52,930 --> 00:04:53,930
to make the video more engaging.

127
00:04:55,070 --> 00:04:56,070
The best travel videos are those

128
00:04:56,670 --> 00:04:57,670
with many creative shots in it

129
00:04:58,620 --> 00:04:59,620
that make you feel like you're there.

130
00:05:00,340 --> 00:05:01,340
Also, the more of a
variety of shots you have,

131
00:05:02,370 --> 00:05:03,370
the easier it is for you

132
00:05:03,730 --> 00:05:04,730
to piece the clips together in the edit.

133
00:05:06,070 --> 00:05:07,070
Only around 10% of all the videos I shoot

134
00:05:08,800 --> 00:05:09,800
when it comes to travel type videos,

135
00:05:10,680 --> 00:05:11,680
end up in the edit

136
00:05:12,130 --> 00:05:13,130
as I only take out the best portion

137
00:05:14,440 --> 00:05:15,440
of the video.

138
00:05:15,340 --> 00:05:16,340
As a rule of thumb,

139
00:05:16,330 --> 00:05:17,330
shoot more than you need,

140
00:05:17,640 --> 00:05:18,640
but also be purposeful with your shots

141
00:05:19,990 --> 00:05:20,990
so that it fits with your edit.

142
00:05:21,880 --> 00:05:22,880
This leads me to tip number five,

143
00:05:23,480 --> 00:05:24,480
which is to shoot to edit.

144
00:05:25,210 --> 00:05:26,210
The tendency most beginner filmmakers have

145
00:05:28,120 --> 00:05:29,120
is to shoot everything they see

146
00:05:29,740 --> 00:05:30,740
without giving much thought.

147
00:05:31,480 --> 00:05:32,480
Before you start recording your video,

148
00:05:33,120 --> 00:05:34,120
think about why you're shooting it

149
00:05:34,920 --> 00:05:35,920
and how it fits the overall story

150
00:05:37,160 --> 00:05:38,160
that you will be telling

151
00:05:38,470 --> 00:05:39,470
when editing the video together.

152
00:05:40,170 --> 00:05:41,170
A good idea is to do some pre-planning

153
00:05:42,420 --> 00:05:43,420
to have a rough idea

154
00:05:43,710 --> 00:05:44,710
of how you want the video to look like.

155
00:05:46,030 --> 00:05:47,030
How do you want the people to feel

156
00:05:48,000 --> 00:05:49,000
when they see your video?

157
00:05:49,350 --> 00:05:50,350
And based on that vision
you have in your mind,

158
00:05:51,950 --> 00:05:52,950
you can start shooting more purposefully.

159
00:05:54,640 --> 00:05:55,640
What I like to do is to search

160
00:05:55,860 --> 00:05:56,860
for the music beforehand

161
00:05:57,330 --> 00:05:58,330
to get a good idea of how
the video should feel like.

162
00:06:00,170 --> 00:06:01,170
Also when it comes to transitional shots,

163
00:06:02,140 --> 00:06:03,140
having the edit in mind is very important.

164
00:06:04,770 --> 00:06:05,770
Think about how you
should film the next shot

165
00:06:07,280 --> 00:06:08,280
to match it with the previous shots.

166
00:06:09,400 --> 00:06:10,400
This way, your videos
will have a better flow

167
00:06:11,750 --> 00:06:12,750
and will make more sense in the edit.

168
00:06:13,870 --> 00:06:14,870
So, a bonus tip I have for you guys

169
00:06:16,000 --> 00:06:17,000
